I should say I
have been immensely

00:24:05.760 --> 00:24:09.010
enjoyed to co-teach the
course on a couple of occasion

00:24:09.010 --> 00:24:11.500
with Vladan Vuletic
and Ike Chuang.

00:24:11.500 --> 00:24:13.600
And Ike has made
major contribution

00:24:13.600 --> 00:24:16.640
to the second part of
the course and Vladan

00:24:16.640 --> 00:24:19.580
especially to what
we will be discussing

00:24:19.580 --> 00:24:23.150
in the next few weeks.

00:24:23.150 --> 00:24:33.070
So what I think is unusual-- you
won't find it in many textbooks

00:24:33.070 --> 00:24:39.120
is that we start
out by discussing

00:24:39.120 --> 00:24:43.570
the phenomenon of resonance
of the harmonic oscillator.

00:24:43.570 --> 00:24:49.080
And we will emphasize for
a while the classical part

00:24:49.080 --> 00:24:54.375
but then also, of course, go to
the quantum mechanical aspects

00:24:54.375 --> 00:24:55.870
of resonance.

00:24:55.870 --> 00:25:00.850
Now I have to say this balance
between classical and quantum

00:25:00.850 --> 00:25:04.130
mechanics is something
I will emphasize

00:25:04.130 --> 00:25:06.220
again and again in the course.

00:25:06.220 --> 00:25:10.350
I can guarantee you in this
course I will sometimes ask you

00:25:10.350 --> 00:25:14.330
interesting question, which
challenge your intuition.

00:25:14.330 --> 00:25:17.950
And you will most
likely recognize

00:25:17.950 --> 00:25:23.590
that often when your intuition
goes completely wrong

00:25:23.590 --> 00:25:26.680
it happens because
you believe too much

00:25:26.680 --> 00:25:30.250
or you over-interpret one
aspect of quantum physics.

00:25:30.250 --> 00:25:33.520
If I then tell you, but wait a
moment, now think classically.

00:25:33.520 --> 00:25:35.530
Push the classical
concept further.

00:25:35.530 --> 00:25:39.580
Regard the electron and the
atom as an harmonic oscillator.

00:25:39.580 --> 00:25:43.230
Regard light scattering
as the effect

00:25:43.230 --> 00:25:45.810
not of a quantum mechanical
atom but of a driven harmonic

00:25:45.810 --> 00:25:46.730
oscillator.

00:25:46.730 --> 00:25:50.610
Suddenly, a lot of things which
come out of quantum mechanics

00:25:50.610 --> 00:25:52.590
make much more sense.

00:25:52.590 --> 00:25:56.750
So I've often seen when I had
a conflict in my understanding.

00:25:56.750 --> 00:26:01.520
And it's a semi-classical and
quantum mechanical explanation,

00:26:01.520 --> 00:26:06.560
I've learned to trust much more
the semi-classical explanation.

00:26:06.560 --> 00:26:09.930
So that's why I feel it's
important to understand

00:26:09.930 --> 00:26:11.700
the classical aspects.

00:26:11.700 --> 00:26:13.770
And usually I would
also say understand

00:26:13.770 --> 00:26:18.760
the means to really
understand it's limits.

00:26:18.760 --> 00:26:22.300
And often I feel you can
understand the phenomenon only

00:26:22.300 --> 00:26:25.400
when you have a quantum
aspect, a classical aspect,

00:26:25.400 --> 00:26:29.450
and we know exactly where they
overlap and where they differ.

00:26:29.450 --> 00:26:33.910
So to see even quantum
mechanical objects occasionally

00:26:33.910 --> 00:26:38.810
from the classical perspective
provides additional insight.

00:26:38.810 --> 00:26:41.940
So therefore, I would
emphasize classical aspects.

00:26:41.940 --> 00:26:44.375
And for instance, it
may come for many of who

00:26:44.375 --> 00:26:47.840
as a surprise and you
will see that next week

00:26:47.840 --> 00:26:53.901
that some aspects like the
generalized Rabi frequency,

00:26:53.901 --> 00:26:56.150
which you all or many of you
have seen for a two level

00:26:56.150 --> 00:26:58.330
system.

00:26:58.330 --> 00:27:01.590
We find it in
classical resonance.

00:27:01.590 --> 00:27:06.970
Just the classic equation
of motion of a gyroscope

00:27:06.970 --> 00:27:09.150
has a generalized
Rabi frequency.

00:27:09.150 --> 00:27:11.960
And I do feel that
it is absolutely

00:27:11.960 --> 00:27:15.200
important for the understanding
of concepts that you know

00:27:15.200 --> 00:27:16.696
where do the concepts emerge?

00:27:16.696 --> 00:27:17.320
Where are they?

00:27:17.320 --> 00:27:21.610
Are they already there in
classical physics and survive

00:27:21.610 --> 00:27:23.100
in quantum physics?

00:27:23.100 --> 00:27:28.450
Or is it something new,
which is genuinely quantum.

00:27:28.450 --> 00:27:31.900
So yes, I will teach a little
bit more classical physics

00:27:31.900 --> 00:27:33.620
than in the standard
[INAUDIBLE] course.

00:27:33.620 --> 00:27:39.310
But because I've seen within
my own research experience

00:27:39.310 --> 00:27:42.680
that it's healthy to shape
the intuition for the fuller

00:27:42.680 --> 00:27:45.716
understanding of the
systems we're dealing with.

00:27:49.330 --> 00:27:55.300
So residence is an
overarching theme here.

00:27:55.300 --> 00:27:59.580
But then we have to
introduce our main players.

00:27:59.580 --> 00:28:01.860
The atoms come to stage.

00:28:01.860 --> 00:28:09.480
And we want to understand
the electronic structure,

00:28:09.480 --> 00:28:11.980
the fine structure, the
hyperfine structure,

00:28:11.980 --> 00:28:14.220
you're going to
understand what happens in

00:28:14.220 --> 00:28:18.210
magnetic, electric, and
electromagnetic light fields.

00:28:22.380 --> 00:28:26.090
We want to understand
in a deep way

00:28:26.090 --> 00:28:29.013
how do atoms interact
with radiation.

00:28:33.520 --> 00:28:34.779
This also leads us.

00:28:34.779 --> 00:28:35.820
There's a big difference.

00:28:35.820 --> 00:28:38.403
You would say, well, what's the
difference when atoms interact

00:28:38.403 --> 00:28:41.080
with microwave and atoms
interact with light.

00:28:41.080 --> 00:28:45.640
Well light or at high
frequency spontaneous emission

00:28:45.640 --> 00:28:46.660
becomes important.

00:28:46.660 --> 00:28:49.020
And then you have an
open quantum system.

00:28:49.020 --> 00:28:51.460
You have an [INAUDIBLE],
which couples automatically

00:28:51.460 --> 00:28:52.920
to many, many states.

00:28:52.920 --> 00:28:56.740
So that's why radiation
is different from just

00:28:56.740 --> 00:29:00.140
electric and magnetic fields
because of the presence of all

00:29:00.140 --> 00:29:03.590
the vacuum modes, and
we'll talk a lot about it.

00:29:08.390 --> 00:29:11.210
There's one special aspect
about the cost, which

00:29:11.210 --> 00:29:15.020
I don't think I've seen in
textbooks in the same way.

00:29:15.020 --> 00:29:19.170
We are singling out
in a rather long unit

00:29:19.170 --> 00:29:23.120
the aspect of line shape.

00:29:23.120 --> 00:29:25.255
OK, we talk a lot about
an atom as a resonance.

00:29:25.255 --> 00:29:27.730
But when you measure
the resonance,

00:29:27.730 --> 00:29:29.330
there is a line shape.

00:29:29.330 --> 00:29:32.680
And I found it
extremely insightful

00:29:32.680 --> 00:29:35.680
when I first saw Dave Pritchard
doing it in his atomic physics

00:29:35.680 --> 00:29:39.500
course to just talk
about all aspects which

00:29:39.500 --> 00:29:44.550
modify a resonance from a data
function from a stick diagram

00:29:44.550 --> 00:29:46.640
into a real shape.

00:29:46.640 --> 00:29:47.770
It can be doppled up water.

00:29:47.770 --> 00:29:49.470
It can be finite
lifetime broadening.

00:29:49.470 --> 00:29:52.476
It can be inhomogenous field.

00:29:52.476 --> 00:29:54.225
But there are lots of
interesting effects.

00:29:54.225 --> 00:29:57.250
And By discussing
them all together

00:29:57.250 --> 00:30:00.240
you gain major insight.

00:30:00.240 --> 00:30:07.810
So we discuss how photon recoil,
how the velocity of atoms

00:30:07.810 --> 00:30:09.950
effect the line shape.

00:30:09.950 --> 00:30:13.500
And if you think you've
understood everything,

00:30:13.500 --> 00:30:20.265
I will talk to you about in a
very counter intunitive aspect

00:30:20.265 --> 00:30:24.460
of line shapes named
Dicke narrowing.

00:30:24.460 --> 00:30:26.990
If you put atoms
in the environment,

00:30:26.990 --> 00:30:28.880
you would say they collide.

00:30:28.880 --> 00:30:31.270
This should lead to
collision and broadening.

00:30:31.270 --> 00:30:35.330
But there is one aspect where
collisions lead to narrowing.

00:30:35.330 --> 00:30:38.390
And that's sort of a highlight
of this chapter which really

00:30:38.390 --> 00:30:41.070
sort of shows you
how actually all

00:30:41.070 --> 00:30:45.215
of those broadening mechanisms
are somehow connected.

00:30:49.100 --> 00:30:57.840
Finally, and this puts us more
towards the end of the course,

00:30:57.840 --> 00:31:03.060
we want to understand what
happens when atoms interact not

00:31:03.060 --> 00:31:06.840
just with one photon
but several photons.

00:31:06.840 --> 00:31:11.470
And then we talk about
multiple photon processes.

00:31:11.470 --> 00:31:13.810
I should actually
say that I'm also

00:31:13.810 --> 00:31:17.070
emphasizing the multi
photon process a lot.

00:31:17.070 --> 00:31:19.070
I mean, often we just
simply do a transition

00:31:19.070 --> 00:31:20.450
between two levels.

00:31:20.450 --> 00:31:23.450
And there is a operator that can
be single photon or two photon

00:31:23.450 --> 00:31:25.930
operator, yes.

00:31:25.930 --> 00:31:29.560
But to understand the multi
photon aspect is important.

00:31:29.560 --> 00:31:33.750
And maybe to just give
you one aspect of it,

00:31:33.750 --> 00:31:36.330
when you think you do
one photon physics,

00:31:36.330 --> 00:31:38.610
often, you do two
photon physics.

00:31:38.610 --> 00:31:42.210
A lot of people think atoms
can absorb the photon.

00:31:42.210 --> 00:31:43.890
I've never seen
in my life an atom

00:31:43.890 --> 00:31:45.480
which has absorbed a photon.

00:31:45.480 --> 00:31:47.530
The photon is
immediately readmitted.

00:31:47.530 --> 00:31:49.170
It's a scattering event.

00:31:49.170 --> 00:31:53.020
An atom cannot absorb the photon
for good because the lifetime

00:31:53.020 --> 00:31:55.020
of the excited state is short.

00:31:55.020 --> 00:31:59.910
So when you think absorption
is a single photon event,

00:31:59.910 --> 00:32:01.830
there is a limitation
where, yes, you're

00:32:01.830 --> 00:32:03.850
allowed to think about it.

00:32:03.850 --> 00:32:07.340
But if you get confused
and it will confuse you,

00:32:07.340 --> 00:32:10.420
then you need the fact that
every absorption process

00:32:10.420 --> 00:32:12.415
is actually a two
photon process.

00:32:12.415 --> 00:32:14.080
Photon in and photon out.

00:32:14.080 --> 00:32:17.840
And sometimes by remembering
that it's not single photons,

00:32:17.840 --> 00:32:20.280
there are always two
photons involved,

00:32:20.280 --> 00:32:23.826
it helps you to avoid some
pitfalls of the similar photon

00:32:23.826 --> 00:32:25.490
picture.

00:32:25.490 --> 00:32:27.680
So therefore, multi photon, yes.

00:32:27.680 --> 00:32:30.510
It's not just high intensity
to photo transitions

00:32:30.510 --> 00:32:31.970
and atomic and such.

00:32:31.970 --> 00:32:34.630
It's also about the
deeper understanding.

00:32:34.630 --> 00:32:36.880
How does the single photon
interact with atoms?

00:32:40.770 --> 00:32:45.140
And finally, there
is something which

00:32:45.140 --> 00:32:47.740
has fascinated many physicists.

00:32:47.740 --> 00:32:50.440
The question about coherence.

00:32:50.440 --> 00:32:55.380
And coherence is as
fascinating as it is diverse

00:32:55.380 --> 00:33:00.260
because coherence can
have as many aspects

00:33:00.260 --> 00:33:05.140
and has many implications.

00:33:05.140 --> 00:33:10.040
And I also like a lot in
this traditional MIT cause

00:33:10.040 --> 00:33:13.384
that coherence is sort of
singled out as a chapter.

00:33:13.384 --> 00:33:15.550
And now I'll tell you about
all the different phases

00:33:15.550 --> 00:33:18.180
of coherence in
this chapter and not

00:33:18.180 --> 00:33:21.790
scattered throughout
the whole course.

00:33:21.790 --> 00:33:23.560
We have coherence
in single atoms.

00:33:26.390 --> 00:33:29.030
The simplest one is the
coherent superposition

00:33:29.030 --> 00:33:35.980
of two level, which is so
simple that it's almost boring.

00:33:35.980 --> 00:33:38.850
But there is an
enormous richness

00:33:38.850 --> 00:33:42.060
when we put in a third letter.

00:33:42.060 --> 00:33:43.900
About 20 years ago,
an understanding

00:33:43.900 --> 00:33:46.540
of three level
physics has really

00:33:46.540 --> 00:33:49.410
created a new
frontier in the field.

00:33:49.410 --> 00:33:51.090
Let me just tell you buzz words.

00:33:51.090 --> 00:33:52.510
Lasing without inversion.

00:33:52.510 --> 00:33:55.250
